name: decimemide

Aniline, the simplest aromatic amine, has a melting point of −6 °C. The presence of the amide group typically increases the melting point because of the potential for hydrogen bonding and the resonance stability of the amide bond. In similar small molecules, an amide group can raise the melting point by approximately 80-100 °C. The methoxy groups (two in this case) should have a lower impact than the amide due to their inability to hydrogen bond as strongly, but their ability to donate electron density to the ring through resonance could still stabilize the solid structure somewhat; each may raise the melting point by around 10-20 °C. The long aliphatic chain (decyl group) present in the molecule generally decreases the melting point due to the increase in the entropy of the molecule, which can typically decrease the melting point by about 40-50 °C when compared to a similar molecule without such a long chain. Combining these factors, the increases from the amide and methoxy groups must be contrasted against the decrease caused by the decyl chain.
Prediction: Starting with the aniline-like basic unit (−6 °C), adding for the amide group (+90 °C), two methoxy groups (+2 x 15 °C), and then subtracting for the decyl chain (−45 °C), the predicted melting point of decimemide would be: −6 (base) + 90 (amide) + 30 (2 x methoxy) - 45 (decyl chain) = 69 °C
